#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:3
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:491
msgid "FITS Viewer Live Stacker"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:5
msgid "|FITS Viewer Live Stacker|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:7
msgid "The FITS Viewer Live Stacker (Live Stacker) stacks and displays subframes. It monitors a directory so can be used to stack the existing contents of the directory and / or to add new subframes as they are taken during a live session."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:12
msgid "Multiple Live Stackers can be run to monitor different directories. These Live Stackers can be run as separate FitsViewer windows or as multiple tabs within a single FitsViewer tab. In addition, it is possible to run Live Stacker as a standalone process which is still under the control of KStars (so it is stopped when KStars itself is stopped) but has its own process space within the operating system."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:19
msgid "Live Stacker follows the FitsViewer architectural approach of displaying the result (in this case the stacked image) and allowing existing functionality such as rotation, object highlighting, histogram manipulation, etc. to be run on the image. The stacked image can be saved by the user using the existing Save functionality."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:25
msgid "Live Stacker operates an option webserver to serve up images to devices such as phones and tablets with web-browsers. This allows the stacked image to be viewed on individuals' devices, for example, at star parties and outreach events."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:30
msgid "Live Stacker operates on .fits and .xisf files. They can be either mono or color."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:33
msgid "Dark and Flat master files may optionally be specified to improve image quality."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:36
msgid "Each section of the Live Stacker input / output widgets are enclosed within a minimize widget that allows the block to be either expanded or minimized."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:39
msgid "Following is a description of the UI widgets:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:41
msgid "Stack Directory: This is the directory that Live Stacker will watch. Any files in the directory will be stacked when the Live Stacking process is started, and as new files (subs) are added to the directory these will be added to the existing stack."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:46
msgid "Stack Directory Button: Launches a directory dialog box to choose a directory."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:49
msgid "Multi-Channel (down arrow) button: Toggles between a single channel (either mono or color) subs and multi-channel. Multi-channel allows the user to combine mono subs into a color image. In this mode Red, Green and Blue must be specified and optionally Luminance can be added."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:54
msgid "Proc / Fail / Total: Output statistics of the number of subs Processed successfully, Failed and the Total. The Total is the number of subs in the directory."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:58
msgid "Webcast Button: Launch the webcast dialog that allows Live Stacker to start or stop webcasting the stacked images in the session."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:61
msgid "Start Button: This button has 3 states:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:63
msgid "\"Start\": Pressing the button runs the stacking process on any subs in Stack Directory and watches the directory for new subs. Button text changes to \"Stop\"."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:67
msgid "\"Stop\": Pressing the button stops watching the directory and cancels any in-flight stacking operation. Button text changes to \"Cancelling...\"."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:70
msgid "\"Cancelling...\": Button cannot be pressed. When the cancel operation completes, the button text resets to \"Start\" and the user can start another stacking process."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:74
msgid "Live Stacker Monitor button: Launches the Live Stacker Monitor window. See the section on Live Stacker Monitor for more details."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:77
msgid "Calc SNR: Switch to turn on or off calculation of SNR for each sub and the stacked image. Usually useful to turn on, but if performance is key this can be toggled off."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:80
msgid "SNR Av / Min / Max: Output statistics of the subs processed so far. Average SNR / Minimum SNR / Maximum SNR."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:83
msgid "Memory Widget: Displays the amount of memory the current process is using as a percentage of the available memory. Try to keep memory usage in the Green (<50% of available) rather than Amber (<70%) or Red (>=70%). Double click the widget to hide text and just display the progress bar."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:89
msgid "Image SNR: This is the SNR of the stacked image at that time."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:91
msgid "Save Settings Button. This saves the configuration of the Live Stacker to disk."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:94
msgid "Help button: Launches web documentation for Live Stacker."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:96
msgid "Calibration Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:98
msgid "This section changes depending on whether single channel or multi-channel mode is selected. In single channel mode there is 1 dark and 1 flat associated with the stack dir. In multi-channel mode there is a dark and flat associated with each of the 4 stack dirs: Red, Green, Blue and Luminance."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:103
msgid "Master Dark: Blank or pathname to a Master Dark .fits file to be used to calibrate subs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:106
msgid "Master Dark Button: Launches a file picker dialog box to choose a Master Dark."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:109
msgid "Master Flat: Blank or pathname to a Master Flat .fits file to be used to calibrate subs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:112
msgid "Master Flat Button: Launches a file picker dialog box to choose a Master Flat."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:115
msgid "Remove Hot Pix: Check to have Live Stacker automatically find and remove hot pixels from subframes."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:118
msgid "Remove Cold Pix: Check to have Live Stacker automatically find and remove cold pixels from subframes."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:121
msgid "Alignment Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:123
msgid "Master Sub: Blank or pathname to the sub to be used to align all other subs to. If blank, the first sub is used as alignment master."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:126
msgid "Master Sub Button: Launches a file picker dialog box to choose the alignment master sub."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:129
msgid "Method: Plate Solve. Use plate solving as the method of aligning subs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:132
msgid "Stacking Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:134
msgid "In Memory Subs. This specifies the maximum number of subs that will be held in-memory at any one time and specifies the number of subs that cause a transition from initial stack to running stack."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:138
msgid "The stacking process will accumulate this number of subs (if available) before stacking them and will continue in batches of this number before stacking. If the number of subs available is less than this then the stacking process runs in order to display the stacked image to the user."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:144
msgid "Once this number of subs is reached, the initial stacking phase completes and intermediate results are then held in order to more rapidly add new, incoming subs to the stack."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:148
msgid "Set this number low to be more efficient with memory usage. However, if you use sigma clipping (or winsorized sigma clipping) setting this too low can compromise results."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:152
msgid "Downscale: Options of None, 2x2, 3x3 and 4x4 are available. This options downscales the subs by the selected factor. For example, if 2x2 is selected than each group of 2x2 pixels is averaged to a single value per color, reducing both the image width and height by a factor of 2. So the number of pixels in each sub is reduced by a factor of 4 which will significantly speed up processing"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:159
msgid "Method:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:161
msgid "Average: Frames are averaged (mean). No pixels are rejected."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:163
msgid "Sigma Clipping: Sigma Clipping is applied to the first \"In Memory Subs\" to be processed. Once accumulated, a pixel stack is built for each pixel in the subs that contains the value of the pixel across all subs. The median and standard deviation of pixel values is calculated any values lying outside the thresholds of Low Sigma and High Sigma are excluded as outliers. The inliers are then used to calculate the stacked image. As new subs arrive they are checked against the saved pixel statistics to determine whether they are inliers or outliers and are processed accordingly."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:173
msgid "Winsorized SC: Similar to Sigma Clipping except where outliers are excluded in Sigma Clipping, they are set to Low Sigma / High Sigma and included in the calculation."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:177
msgid "ImageMM: The ImageMM stacking method based on this paper: https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/1538-3881/adfb72 Basically this can be thought of as a combination of stacking and deconvolution. The method looks to determine the most likely deconvolved stacked image that would have created the set of observed subs. It uses an iterative approach and is extremely resource intensive. This is an experimental approach at this time."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:184
msgid "Frame Weighting:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:186
msgid "Equal: All subs are given an equal weight (=1.0)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:188
msgid "HFR: Subs are weighted by 1 / (Av HFR). So the better the sub, the lower the HFR and the higher the weighting."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:191
msgid "Num Stars: Subs are weighted by Num Stars. So the better the sub, the higher than number of stars detected and the higher the weighting."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:195
msgid "Normalization:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:197
msgid "None: No normalization of subframes is performed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:199
msgid "Linear: Incoming subframes are linear normalized to the existing stack. This is the preferred method as it will stack better with subframes of various background intensity. This option will also deal better with the frame edges to avoid sharp jumps in brightness where subframes have moved slightly during the session."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:204
msgid "Low Sigma (Sigma Clipping and Winsor SC Methods). This is the number of Standard Deviations on the low side of the median to clip pixels out."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:207
msgid "High Sigma (Sigma Clipping and Winsor SC Methods). This is the number of Standard Deviations on the high side of the median to clip pixels out."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:210
msgid "Winsor Cutoff (Winsor SC Method). This is the number of Standard Deviations away from the median to use as cutoff to adjust outlying values before running Sigma Clipping."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:213
msgid "Iteration (ImageMM). This specifies the maximum number of iterations the algorithm will attempt. Increase the number for more accurate performance but at the expense of performance."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:217
msgid "Kappa (ImageMM). Clamps iterative updates in the range 1/kappa to kappa. So kappa=1 means no update for the iteration. Increase kappa for bigger updates but if you see signs of over \"deconvolving\" the image then reduce kappa."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:221
msgid "Alpha (ImageMM). Damping between iterations by blending alpha * this iteration with (1 - alpha) * last iteration."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:224
msgid "Sigma Scale (ImageMM). Reduce calculated image sigma by this scale factor. Reduce if you see ringing artifacts."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:227
msgid "PSF Update (ImageMM). Update PSF every nth iteration. Set to zero to disable. Updating too frequently can lead to artifacts. This is quite computationally intensive."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:230
msgid "Post Processing Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:232
msgid "Post processing options can be turned on / off with the associated minimize widget checkbox. The system temporarily turns off post processing during the initial stacking phase to speed up processing. Thereafter, control is with the user."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:237
msgid "These settings are applied to the stacked image to improve its appearance. There are 3 tools: Deconvolution, Denoising and Sharpening. Typically the parameters to use must be found through experimentation by the user. By changing values and hitting the Reprocess Button, the user can adjust values and rerun the Post Processing without re-running the stacking process."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:243
msgid "Deconvolution Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:245
msgid "Wiener Deconvolution can be applied to the image. The PSF sigma to use must be specified along with an amount."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:248
msgid "Deconv Amount: This is the amount of the Deconvolved image to blend with the original stacked image. The range is between 0 (no deconvolution) to 1 (use only the deconvolved image). Set to 0 to disable Deconvolution."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:252
msgid "PSF Sigma. The PSF Sigma to use in the deconvolution process."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:254
msgid "Denoising Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:256
msgid "Denoise Amount: The amount of denoising to apply. Higher values denoise more. Set to 0 to disable denoising."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:259
msgid "Sharpening Settings:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:261
msgid "A basic Unsharp Mask sharpening algorithm is used."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:263
msgid "Sharpen Amount: The amount of sharpening to apply. Higher values sharpen more. Set to 0 to disable sharpening."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:266
msgid "Sharpen Kernel. The size of the kernel used for sharpening in pixels (usually 5 or 7 works well). Choose an odd integer."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:269
msgid "Sharpen Sigma. The sigma used in the sharpening process."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:271
msgid "Reprocess:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:273
msgid "Reprocess Button. Pressing this button reruns the Post Processing functionality (Deconvolution, Denoising and Sharpening) on the stacked image using the current values of the Post Processing settings. This means that on a stacked image the user can adjust settings and re-run, adjust again and re-run, etc."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:279
msgid "Using Live Stacker for the First Time"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:281
msgid "Here are some suggestions for using Live Stacker for the first time:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:283
msgid "Start in daylight on your imaging computer / setup with some subs you have already taken during a previous imaging session. If you have say 30 subs this will be enough to see how Live Stacker performs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:287
msgid "Select the directory of the subs, and press Start. The default parameters should be relatively memory efficient but may need tweaking."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:290
msgid "See how the Memory Widget performs; you want to keep memory usage Green or at worst Amber intermittently. If you are having issues with performance and / or memory usage then here are the things to speed things up (start at the top and work down the list):"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:295
msgid "Downscale: Usually 2x2 is enough to significantly increase performance with mono subs. Color subs may need more downscaling."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:298
msgid "In Memory Subs: Decrease this number. It will then hold less subs in memory at the same time. Note that for Sigma Clipping and Winsorised SC this will potentially compromise image quality."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:302
msgid "Calibration Files: Adding a dark and or a flat master will improve image quality, potentially significantly, but at the cost of extra processing."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:305
msgid "Frame Weighting: Equal is the most efficient option. Num Stars requires an extra step during Plate Solving so will always be slower. HFR requires the same extra step as Num Stars but also needs more computation so is the slowest option. HFR and Num Stars should, however, yield a better result than Equal weighting."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:311
msgid "Rejection Method: None is much more efficient than the other options (at the cost of a potentially better result)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:314
msgid "You can rerun the stacking process from scratch by just pressing Start, so its easy to adjust parameters and rerun."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:317
msgid "It's recommended to switch off Post Processing during early stages and come back to it later (see below). To do this make sure the Deconv Amount, Denoise Amount and Sharpen Amount are all set to 0."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:321
msgid "When you have a configuration you are happy with press Save Settings and this will be the default configuration for subsequent settings."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:325
msgid "Post Processing"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:327
msgid "When you have the settings for stacking sorted out for your equipment you may wish to try the Post Processing options. Note that the settings you choose will be applied every time Live Stacker displays a stack, e.g. when a new sub is added to the stack. For this reason when you are setting up the stack it is advisable to turn off Post Processing and then when stacking has finished, to experiment with it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:333
msgid "To experiment, set one of the options and press Reprocess. You can then adjust the parameter and press Reprocess again until you have the optimum settings."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:337
msgid "Live Stacker Webcast"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:339
msgid "Pressing the Webcast button launches the Live Stacker Webcast window. This lets you control all aspects of the webcast which allows yourself and others to view stacked images on web-browsers on phones, tablets and computers. This is useful at star parties and outreach events."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:343
msgid "|FITS Viewer Live Stacker Webcast|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:345
msgid "The Webcast is initially stopped but is started by pressing Start. This starts the webserver and also displays a QR code in the dialog. This can be scanned to launch a web-browser on a device at the appropriate URL to receive images. Alternatively the displayed URL can be typed in."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:349
msgid "Multiple devices can be connected."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:351
msgid "As stacking progresses each registered device is automatically updated. The usual features of the device's browser are available. For example, if supported, the image can be user to the device's camera roll. The webpage can be converted to an app by the user (if this is supported on the device). This can be useful as sometimes it gives more screen space to the image and minimises decoration."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:356
msgid "The following widgets are available: Title. Sets a title for the session - which is displayed on the device. Logo L / R: Allows a logo to be displayed to the left and right of the Title. Port: Defaults to 8080 but can be changed if required. Throttle Updates: If short exposures are causing bandwidth issues, setting this with throttle updates to clients. QR Code: Scan the QR code from a device to launch a browser on the URL URL: The URL the webcast is being broadcast on. Start Webcast: Starts the webcast Stop Webcast: Stops the webcast Reset: removes the images history of the webcast. Effectively a Stop Webcast followed by Start Webcast Subscribers: Toggle to show / hide a grid of subscribing devices to the webcast. Close: Close the Webcast dialog (can be reopened at any time)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:370
msgid "Live Stacker Monitor"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:372
msgid "Pressing the Live Stacker Monitor button launches the Live Stacker Monitor window. The purpose of the Monitor is to display more information at the subframe level about the subs being stacked."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:375
msgid "|FITS Viewer Live Stacker Monitor|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:377
msgid "The Monitor displays a grid with 1 row for each sub in the directory / directories selected. The columns are configurable: right click on the column header to display a menu of columns that may be selected or deselected, or double click a column header to remove a column. In addition, the column order may be changed by clicking dragging a column header to a new location."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:382
msgid "Single clicking a column sorts the grid on that column and toggles between an ascending sort and a descending sort."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:385
msgid "The alignment master sub has a yellow background. If a sub fails to process it has a pink background. The \"Highlighting\" checkbox will also highlight cell changes as updates are processed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:388
msgid "Tooltips on the column headers explain what each column represents but in summary the columns represent the stacking workflow with relevant information from each step: 1. Miscellaneous columns: ID, pathname, filename, channel(s) and overall status. 2. Loading: displays timings and status of the load step and SNR of the sub. 3. Plate Solving: displays timings, status, average HFR, number of stars. 4. Stack Waiting: displays timings, status of a sub once loaded before the next stacking step. 5. Calibration: displays timings, status, Hot Pix, Cold Pix. Note that calibration is optional. 6. Alignment: displays timings, status and x, y and rotation of the sub to align with the master. 7. Stacking: displays timings, status and stacking weight."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:398
msgid "A good way to use the Monitor is to select columns that are relevant to you and order by the ID column so most recent subs are at the top."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:402
msgid "Single Channel vs Multi-Channel Mode"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:404
msgid "Live Stacker starts in single channel mode. This allows a single stack of either mono or color subs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:407
msgid "It is also possible to create color images from individual stacks of mono images. To do this, activate multi-channel mode by expanding the stack directory dropdown toggle (see the red box below) which will then display input directories for Red, Green, Blue and Luminance."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:411
msgid "|FITS Viewer Live Stacker MultiChannel|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:413
msgid "Live Stacker will then stack files in each of the directories and then watch the directories for new files. If an RGB stack is required, fill in Red, Green and Blue (and leave Luminance blank). Live Stacker will then process a stack for each channel, apply a \"linear fit\" between channels, and combine into a color image for display."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:418
msgid "Optionally, a Luminance channel can be added to produce an LRGB image. In this mode, the RGB channels are combined with the Luminance channel to produce a single color image."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:421
msgid "Narrowband filter stacks can be combined into color images: SHO, HOO, etc."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:423
msgid "If less than 3 stacks are available, for example whilst doing an HOO image, fill in the same directory to the appropriate channels. E.g. for an HOO image set Red to the Hydrogen directory and Green and Blue to the Oxygen directory."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:428
msgid "Running Live Stackers"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:430
msgid "It's possible to run more than 1 Live Stacker to monitor multiple directories. This would be useful if you are imaging multiple targets or filters and want to keep an eye on everything without having to reset the Live Stacker to a new directory periodically."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:434
msgid "Live Stacker is started by selecting \"Live Stacker...\" from the KStars Skymap. Selecting \"Live Stacker...\" a second time will launch another Live Stacker. Depending on how FITS Viewer is configured will determine whether multiple Live Stacker windows are started (\"Single Window Capture\" unchecked) or whether multiple tabs within a single Live Stacker window are started (\"Single Window Capture\" checked)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:440
msgid "|FITS Viewer Live Stacker Options|"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:442
msgid "By default the tab name for Live Stacker is \"(n) DirectoryPath\" where n is the number of subs in DirectoryPath. Right click on tabname to change the name to whatever you like. This is particularly useful when runing multiple instances of Live Stacker as separate tabs."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: ../../user_manual/fits-viewer-livestacker.rst:447
msgid "The \"Live Stacker own process\" option allows Live Stacker to be started as a separate process. When \"Live Stacker own process\" is unchecked, Live Stacker resides in the KStars / Ekos process space. The advantage of running Live Stacker as its own process is that if it crashes it will not disturb other KStars / Ekos functionality."
msgstr ""

